rkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Melville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from any of the various places in Normandy called Malleville, from Latin <i>mala</i> ‘bad’ + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’.","Irish (mainly Ulster): English surname adopted by bearers of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilmhichíl</b> ‘descendant of <i>Maoilmhichil</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘devotee of (Saint) Michael’.","History: The American novelist Herman Melville (1819–91) was a descendantof the Scottish Melvilles. His maternal grandfather was the revolutionary war general Peter Gansevoort (born 1749 in Albany, NY). His paternal grandfather was Maj. Thomas Melville of Boston. Irish bearers of the name claim descent from Maol Mhichíl, a chief of Síol Muireadhaigh (County Roscommon) in the 9th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Melvin","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Melville   with alternation of final <i>-l</i> and <i>-n</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhín</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of Maoilmhín’, a personal name meaning ‘gentle chieftain’."]},{"name":"Mulville","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Melville  ."]},{"name":"Mellin","meanings":["Scottish (Glamorgan): variant of   Melville  .","German: habitational name from any of various places so called.","English: variant of   Melling  ."]},{"name":"Mulvihill","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Paddy.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoil Mhichíl</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) Michael’. The Anglicized form was sometimes abbreviated into   Melville  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Richard de Melville was born in 1170, in Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Gregory de Melville, was 32 and his mother, Agnes Ross, was 12. He had at least 2 sons with Margaret Pratt. He died in 1215, in Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1170–1215":"1170–1215","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1199–Male":"1199–Surnud","1212–Male":"1212–Surnud","1139–1178":"1139–1178","1158–Female":"1158–Surnud","1139":"1139","1215":"1215","liv. abt. 1174":"umbes 1174","1158":"1158","1212":"1212","1178":"1178","ABT. 1199":"umbes 1199","1199":"1199","1170":"1170","Melville, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","of, Melville, Angus, Scotland":"Angus, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Liberton, Lanark, Scotland":"Liberton, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1170–1215":"1170–1215","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1199–Male":"1199–Kuollut","1212–Male":"1212–Kuollut","1139–1178":"1139–1178","1158–Female":"1158–Kuollut","1139":"1139","1215":"1215","liv. abt. 1174":"noin 1174","1158":"1158","1212":"1212","1178":"1178","ABT. 1199":"noin 1199","1199":"1199","1170":"1170","Melville, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","of, Melville, Angus, Scotland":"Angus, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Liberton, Lanark, Scotland":"Liberton, Lanarkshire, Skotlanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1170–1215":"1170–1215","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1199–Male":"1199–Décédé","1212–Male":"1212–Décédé","1139–1178":"1139–1178","1158–Female":"1158–Décédée","1139":"1139","1215":"1215","liv. abt. 1174":"environ 1174","1158":"1158","1212":"1212","1178":"1178","ABT. 1199":"environ 1199","1199":"1199","1170":"1170","Melville, Midlothian, Scotland":"Midlothian, Écosse, Royaume-Uni","Melville, Lasswade, Midlothian, Scotland":"Lasswade, Midlothian